Originally, I wanted to write about biblical basis homophobic people use as arguments against the LGBTQIA+ community. I also wanted to call out Senator Joel Villanueva for stating that the SOGIE Bill is not urgent and that religious organizations are more important in this country. I also wanted to say something regarding Awra Briguela and the recent abuse she took from the transphobic police of Makati City (during Pride Month, no less). Finally—and this was probably going to be my most controversial blog post, within my circles at least—I wanted to examine God the Almighty's gender identity, sexual orientation, and gender expression and write about it. In that hypothetical blog post that I didn't end up writing, I wanted to make the case that God himself is a <i>masculine-presenting asexual non-binary</i>. This, of course, is to spite those people in the churches who preach that He will burn us in the eternal fires of hell.

And I know, you might be reading this and are now thinking, <i>what in the world does all that psycho-babble mean?</i> And I thought the same too. So I ended up deciding to write this post to explain what <abbr>SOGIESC</abbr> (sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, and sex characteristics) actually is. I hope that by the end of this post, you would no longer think that we are different from anyone else. I hope that by the end of you reading this, you realize that the rights and benefits we are fighting for will actually benefit you too if you are heterosexual.

<aside class="callout callout--info">
  {{ 'info' | icon }}
  <p class="callout__body">In this post, I will use diagrams to help in understanding the terms. These diagrams are by no means exact, and I could have mistakes and flaws in representing different identities, sexualities, and experiences. If you notice that I had made flaws in these diagrams, I urge you to please contact me so that I could correct such mistakes.</p>
</aside>

The first thing I want to do in this first section is to encourage you to throw away everything you know and everything else you think you know about gender and sexuality. We want to tear them all down. Growing up, we were taught that there were two genders, male and female, and everything else either fall under the so-called "third sex" or biological deformations and anomalies.

  <figcaption>
    <p><b>Figure 1:</b> Our old understanding of how genders and sexes work. In this understanding, we see the male and the female as the standard of genders and sexes. Gays and lesbians are considered members of the so-called now-inaccurate "third sex". The concept of being a transgender did not exist in this model, but they are rather considered gays and lesbians as well. Intersex people, or those with biological attributes not typical to male or female, are considered a biological anomaly and were called "hermaphrodite", a term we no longer use today.</p>

Let's start with what we are most familiar with. Before this, when you hear gender and sex, perhaps the first thing that comes to your mind is your genitals, what's in your pants. That's what we were taught in the old model of gender, that it is solely based on people's genitals and power to procreate.

In the new model, <dfn class="weight-700">sex characteristics</dfn>, the biological and physical attributes you are born with or grew up with, are just one component. Here, we have the usual male and female. However, we also have intersex people, those who have biological or physical characteristics that are not typically male or female that they acquired on their birth or during puberty. 

Notice that this component is not a continuous spectrum. We just have either male or female, and a bunch of different configurations for intersex people. Intersex people have different biological attributes that make them intersex, and a lot of times, one intersex person will have different intersex characteristics from another. One intersex person may grow breasts as with a female even if they were born with male biology, while another gets the opposite. Another intersex person may grow up and live their life as a man, but their body starts developing female attributes during puberty. There are also people born with a penis but have a functioning uterus inside their bodies. Intersex attributes vary from person to person, that is why I represented it with a dashed line.

<dfn class="weight-700">Gender identity</dfn> is how you see and know yourself. Gender identity is a matter of identifying with the sex you are born with. If you identify with the sex you are born with (e.g. you were born male and you identify as a man, or you were born female and you identify as a woman), you are <i>cisgender</i>, from Latin cis-  meaning "on this side of". If you don't identify with your assigned sex at birth, then you are <i>transgender</i>, from Latin trans-  meaning "on the other side of". If for any reason, you feel that you identify with both male and female identities, you might be <i>non-binary</i>, which means you don't subscribe to the idea of two genders, but rather fluid in how you see yourself. Or maybe your gender identity doesn't define you or it doesn't matter to you or your general identity. Some people don't identify at all with any of the male or female genders, and we call them <i>agender</i>.

We can also look at gender identity as different levels of man-ness and woman-ness. In this way of looking at gender identity, we disregard the biological component of gender completely, which is totally fine. Our identities can be defined with our without looking at our body parts, whichever we are more comfortable with.

This view of gender identity allows us to understand that gender widely  differs from person to person. And it's very probable that at times, even if you are confident in the fact that you are a woman, you still feel like there's a little bit of a man in you. Or even if you identify as a man, you might feel that you have a little bit of woman-ness in you. This is your gender identity at play.  It's how your brain internally understands your biological chemistry (e.g. hormones).

This one's a bit more abstract, and because of that, a lot of people think it is arbitrary, especially when they see a lot of these new labels for gender come up. <i>Wouldn't I be able to just invent new genders? Wouldn't this make it possible for me to just tell everyone that I am a woman, even though I am a man?</i>  This is a good question, a philosophical one! And to answer it, I ask another question: would you, as a man, ever tell your family and friends that you are actually, in fact, a woman? Would you tell everyone you know that you don't identify as a man, but rather, a woman? Would you be able to come to work one day and tell your work bestie that instead of knowing you your entire life as a woman, that you are actually a "genderqueef", a gender that you just invented? Would you be able to do all these in all seriousness and come through with them? 

If your answer to these questions are a lot of no's, then you have your answer to your question. Gender identity is literally that—your *identity*. It is not something you just arbitrarily change; it is a fundamental part of your existence. You wouldn't change it willy-nilly the same way you won't change your legal name just because you felt like it, and then change it back again when you no longer want to go by your new name.

Another thing to note is that people can call themselves whatever they want, and these labels they put on their genders are not for you, but for them and people like them so they could find each other, as well as resources that will help problems unique to them. Most of the time, you just need to be polite and respectful, and that entails that before you ask about someone's gender, you ask yourself why you want or need to know (no, "I'm just curious" is not a valid reason for asking, please and thank you). If you want to know someone's gender identity, you got to make yourself a safe space for them and everyone else so they open it up to you when they are ready and if  they want to.

### On gender-affirming surgeries and transitioning

You might have heard of transitioning and gender-affirming surgeries. While this post is not meant to be an exhaustive reference for all things gender, I want to include this one. Some transgender people undergo transitioning, which involves coming out to everyone in their lives and living as the gender they identify with. This is called <b>social transitioning</b>. Some transgender people also opt to undergo <b>medical transitioning</b>. Some of them are satisfied with hormonal transitioning, where they take hormones to make their bodies transition into the gender they identify with. Some of them also undergo top (removal of breasts for female-to-male transitioning, or breast implants for male-to-female transitioning) and bottom surgery (surgery involving a persons genitals).

A lot of transgender people are satisfied with social transitioning, because as far as everyone is concerned, they are the gender they identify with and they don't need medical transitioning. Some of them also opt for social transitioning because their bodies will not be able to transition medically, and this is also fine.

Note that none of these are required for transgender people. You don't have to transition or undergo medical procedures to prove that you are transgender. How you see yourself is enough to validate your identity.

Gender expression is how you dress, speak, and behave. For this component, we measure our leaning towards masculinity and femininity. This can be completely disconnected to your sex characteristics and gender identity. You may identify as a male, but you like dressing up femininely, or the opposite. (e.g. the comedian Tekla, a lot of drag queens, butch lesbians, etc.) There are also people, including me, who fluctuate between masculine and feminine expressions, and this is the case for most people. You can also express yourself in a way that's ambiguous in terms of gender roles, and we call this <b>androgynous</b>. Some people like to dress in a way that deliberately contradicts what is the norm for their gender, and we call these expressions <b>gender non-conforming</b>.

<aside class="callout callout--info">
  {{ 'info' | icon }}
  <p class="callout__body">The words <b>androgynous</b> and <b>unisex</b> are closely related terms that have different usage. Unisex is for articles of clothing. Androgynous is for people. We can describe articles of clothing and entire outfits as androgynous but we should never describe people as unisex out of respect for them.</p>
</aside>

Most of the times, your gender expression is fluid. Depending on how much societal norms affect you and your daily life, you might come to work in masculine clothes, go out with your friends dressed femininely, and stay at home dressed androgynously—all at the same day.

Sexual orientation is the person you want to fall in love with and have intimacy with. People who are exclusively attracted to people of their opposite gender or sex are called <i>heterosexual</i> or straight people. People who are exclusively attracted to people of the same gender or sex are called <i>homosexual</i> people. People who are attracted to two or more genders or sexes are called <i>bisexual</i> people. People who don't consider a person's sex or gender to be attracted to them sexually/romantically are called <i>pansexual</i>. And those who experience little to no sexual or romantic attraction to anyone are called <i>asexual</i> and <i>aromantic</i> respectively.

## Some reminders
- Calling people as <i>homosexuals</i> might not be the best course of action. In the past, while the term accurately represents the sexual orientation, <i>homosexual</i> has also been used in negative contexts. These days, homosexual people like to call themselves gay or lesbian. 
- The term <i>gay</i> can sometimes be used to refer to both gays and lesbians.
- In Filipino/Tagalog, the terms <i lang="tl">bading</i> and <i lang="tl">bakla</i> are generally accepted as long as you don't use them to offend gay people. The Bisaya term <i lang="tl">bayot</i> is offensive in Tagalog-speaking areas, so if you're not speaking in Binisaya/Cebuano, it's best not to use this term. <i>Faggot</i> is a slur, don't use it anywhere unless you are a part of the LGBTQIA+ community.
- <i>Tomboy</i> is different from <i>lesbian</i>. <dfn>Tomboy</dfn> is a gender expression where a woman expresses herself in a masculine way. <dfn>Lesbian</dfn> is a sexual orientation where a woman is attracted to the same gender or sex. Not all lesbians are tomboys, and not all tomboys are lesbians.

## On God's gender
At the start of this article, I mentioned that God is a masculine-presenting asexual non-binary. I mean no offense to the Christian community, and what I'm saying right now are all based on biblical texts. I'm inclined to think that you would also agree with this description of God after reading this entire post. To those curious, I'll explain what I mean:
- **God is non-binary**. As a spirit person, God does not have a physical body, and therefore does not have biological sex characteristics. With this in mind, He is non-binary.
- **God is asexual**. With no physical body with genitals subject to biological chemistry, God has no need or want for sexual activities. Therefore, he is asexual.
- **God is masculine-presenting**. While non-binary and asexual, God likes to refer to himself using the pronouns he/him. In a lot of contexts, he has referred to Himself as a Father and (if you believe in the Trinitarian doctrine) a Son. When He (as God the Son) came down as a human, He manifested himself to be born as a male human. He likes to present Himself in a masculine way. But there are also times when God referred to himself in a feminine way, like that one time Jesus likened Himself to a hen with chicks. (Matthew 23:37) He also likened Himself to a mother multiple times. (Isaiah 42:14; 49:15; 66:13; Hosea 13:8) Finally, in certain contexts, He used both masculine and feminine imagery to refer to Himself. (Deuteronomy 32:11–12, 18) Like what we learned in Gender Expressions, this is a normal fluctuating expression of gender, that while God use both masculine and feminine ways of expressing Himself, He is mainly masculine-presenting.

I hope you view this as an actual respectful analysis of God's gender through the lens of our current understanding. Of course, God is a spirit being, and the Bible was written during a time when we didn't even have an inkling of how complicated human gender is. But inquiries about the nature of God has always been part of human curiosities, and this effort is in no way different. You may agree or disagree with this analysis, which are fine either way.

## Conclusion

They say the biggest enemy of hate is not love but knowledge. Sort of true in a way, since it is in our nature to hate or be afraid of things we don't understand. A huge lot of opposition against the LGBTQIA+ community stems from the fact that for the longest time, we did not understand how genders worked and why people who were not aligned with the status quo kept appearing. I feel it deep within me that I have a duty to queer people like me, especially the young ones, to do something about this hate. And I know some people, especially those who'd known me for a long time, are especially tired of hearing, watching, and reading about me speak about these things. But I feel like I owe this to an entire community. Just a mere century ago, homosexuality was considered a psychological disorder, and now we discovered that it's actually not a disorder but rather a natural manifestation of human personality. We need to learn, and we need to get on with the times. If you stay on a station for too long and keep skipping trains that pass by, the terminal will soon close. This is new information, and it challenges our understanding of a fundamental part of our identities, so of course it is natural to be apprehensive and have a hard time accepting it, but it never hurts to try otherwise. 

People like me are being harassed, abused, and killed legally everywhere in the world. We need more allies—at work, at home, at school, on the streets, in the media, in the senate—everywhere. We need your help. Or else, countless brilliant minds whose only fault is to exist will be lost to us forever. And these brilliant but dead minds could be one of your own, too. It could be your daughter, or your son, or your mother, or your father, or your uncle, or your best friend, or your lover. Our fight for equal rights and against discrimination is not yet over. And your help for us has started now, by learning more about yourself.
